00:48:01.000 --> 00:48:04.330
you know, from our
organization's perspective

00:48:04.330 --> 00:48:06.520
and as we continue to
serve those who serve,

00:48:06.520 --> 00:48:11.910
we look at service a little more
expansively than just the person

00:48:11.910 --> 00:48:13.300
who puts on the uniform.

00:48:13.300 --> 00:48:17.880
I think if there's a gap between
the civilian military divide,

00:48:17.880 --> 00:48:22.630
I think there's a chasm
between what our country knows

00:48:22.630 --> 00:48:25.220
about military spouses and
caregivers and the service

00:48:25.220 --> 00:48:27.920
and the sacrifice
that they made.

00:48:27.920 --> 00:48:30.840
As we get into September
11th tomorrow and closer

00:48:30.840 --> 00:48:34.860
to Veterans' Day, you know, I'd
ask those in this room and those

00:48:34.860 --> 00:48:39.020
on the webinar to really
think about military spouses

00:48:39.020 --> 00:48:42.320
and caregivers from the vantage
point that they served too.

00:48:42.320 --> 00:48:45.860
They've served and sacrificed
for our country, and as we think

00:48:45.860 --> 00:48:48.510
about how we can meet their
needs, we need to think

00:48:48.510 --> 00:48:52.050
about the entire
family that serves

00:48:52.050 --> 00:48:54.280
around that service member.

